The eight-nation Arctic Council said the annual average amount of sea ice around the North Pole has decreased about 8 percent in 30 years because of global warming fueled by greenhouse gas emissions. The treaty has been ratified by at least 140 nations. ``To some, that's just the difference between putting a jacket on and off,'' said Clive Tesar, of the council's Indigenous Peoples' Secretariat. The softening permafrost has already driven some polar animals further north. The council believes temperatures in the Arctic will increase 3 degrees Celsius (5.4 degrees Fahrenheit) by 2080. 